#   BLAME-005: emit blame as per-commit hunks (header = commit, body = source)

Blame today prepends a fixed-width gutter to every source line (`graf/BLAME.c`
~line 757: `BLAME_HW` chars + an `L`-tok before each line), so the commit
metadata **shares the line with the code**. That is the root of the bro
breakage: the gutter is counted in the wrap width (wraps early), soft-wrap
mangles the table, and the line can't be syntax-highlighted. Restructure the
output into `dog/HUNK` hunks — one per commit-run — moving the metadata off the
code line entirely. See [Projector], [Bro], [BLAME-004].

##  Input

### Context
 -  Per-line gutter shares the source line → (a) wrong wrap width (counts the
    gutter), (b) garbled table on soft-wrap, (c) no syntax highlighting, (d)
    blame has no highlighting at all though it should.
 -  A `hunk` is `{ ron60 ts; ron60 verb; u8cs uri; text + tok32 syntax tags }`
    (`dog/HUNK.h`). That triple is the DATA; HOW it's drawn (header layout,
    highlighting, wrap) is the SHARED bro renderer's job (`HUNKu8sFeedText/
    Color/Html`), not the producer's. So blame's only job is to PRODUCE hunks.

### Goals
 -  Emit blame as a HUNK stream: each maximal run of consecutive lines sharing
    one commit = **one content hunk** carrying `ts` = commit time, `verb`,
    `uri` = the commit ref (`commit:?<sha>`, clickable via the existing
    renderer), and the run's verbatim source as the hunk text + `tok32`
    syntax tags.
 -  Drop the per-line `BLAME_HW`+`L`-tok gutter entirely — the commit no longer
    rides the source line, so the shared renderer can highlight/wrap the body
    correctly (that's where the bro bugs get fixed, for ALL projectors).
 -  Keep graf's blame walk (per-line attribution) — only regroup the emit.

### Constraints
 -  `blame:` stays graf-owned; output is a `dog/HUNK` stream. Presentation is
    OUT OF SCOPE here — it belongs to the shared bro renderer.

##  WIP

### Design decisions
 -  No header-style decision lives here: header layout / 1-line-run density /
    colors are the shared renderer's presentation, not blame's. Blame emits
    `{ts, verb, uri}`+body; the renderer draws it.
 -  Streaming: emit each run-hunk as produced (don't accumulate the whole
    file) — this also removes the fixed-`outbuf` overflow, so it **subsumes**
    [BLAME-004] once landed (BLAME-004 is the minimal crash fix meanwhile).

